<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Huntingdon shares fall 28p on warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Huntingdon International Holdings fell almost a fifth yesterday
after the life sciences, engineering and environmental company issued a
second profits warning in 12 months and blamed the parlous state of the
green industry.
The shares closed 28p lower at 119p.
Huntingdon said trading conditions in its US and UK-based engineering and
environmental services division were even weaker than the board had
indicated when annual results showing a near-40 per cent slide in pre-tax
profits to Pounds 8.79m were published in December.
It now planned to bring in specialist consultants to conduct a four-week
review of environmental and engineering operations.
'To expect environmental matters will provide a gratuitous upturn in our
fortunes is no way to run a business. We have recognised that - perhaps we
should have recognised it sooner,' said Mr Christopher Cliffe, finance
director.
'We have to decide whether the diversification programme into engineering
and environmental services still makes sense in view of the absence of
governments' willingness to enforce compliance and sign off any major
infrastructure projects in the UK,' he said.
Moreover, new legislation in the US has yet to materialise. The group had
hoped new laws would increase the workload of the 1,800 people it employs in
engineering and environmental services operations at 70 sites in the US.
The business, which now accounts for about 52 per cent of Huntingdon's total
revenue following last year's Pounds 3m rationalisation, was started up in
1985, growing mainly through a series of small acquisitions until 1991 when
it ran into the US recession.
</TEXT>
