<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Menzies pleases City with advance to Pounds
6.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Menzies, chairman of the retail and wholesale chain which carries
his name, said that the group's interim results continued to show the
improving trend of the last few years.
In the six months to October 30 pre-tax profits jumped from Pounds 3.8m to
Pounds 6.3m, though Mr Ranald Noel-Paton, group managing director, said they
were skewed by Pounds 500,000 of losses last time from the now sold
Hammick's retail bookshop chain, and by halved interest charges of Pounds
800,000 this time.
The reduced interest costs reflected, he said, the strength of the group and
its cashflow as well as the management of working capital.
On the profits front, he said he was more encouraged by the 20 per cent
increase in operating profits on continuing operations to Pounds 7.1m
(Pounds 5.9m). The shares rose 30p to 654p on the day.
The main engine of growth was the distribution side which, as a high volume,
low margin business 'concentrates the mind', according to Mr Noel-Paton.
He echoed his chairman in his disappointment over the short shrift the
government gave the outcome of the MMC's 18-month inquiry into the
distribution of newspapers in England and Wales, but was confident the group
would not suffer from the government's intended liberalisation of newspaper
wholesaling.
TBD (home entertainment and book wholesaling) and Universal Office Supplies
both performed well in the period.
The retail side showed a similar pattern as previously, with Early Learning
Centres 'really performing well' with 'a sales rise in double digits'
balancing the John Menzies Retail chain, which is being restructured.
ELC has 177 outlets, two of which are superstores, which carry clothing and
nursery goods as well as toys and books. Mr Noel-Paton said this new format
had 'huge turnover'.
JM Retail consists of 276 stores, some 150 of which are to be redesigned
away from generalist outlets to multi-specialist shops.
Mr Noel-Paton also revealed a 6.5 per cent like-for-like increase in
retailing sales over the Christmas period with music sales at the forefront.
Group turnover climbed to Pounds 573.1m (Pounds 539.3m) and the interim
dividend is lifted to 4.1p (3.8p), payable from earnings per share more than
doubled to 5.9p (2.9p).
</TEXT>
