<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / American Express to spin off Lehman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
American Express is to pump Dollars 1.25bn into its Lehman Brothers
investment banking subsidiary to enable it to become a free-standing firm,
marking the credit card group's final withdrawal from the securities and
investment banking arenas.
The recapitalisation signals a decision by American Express not to float
Lehman, as had been expected. Instead, it is to issue shares in the company
to existing American Express shareholders, and will receive a share of
future Lehman profits of up to Dollars 550m.
The spin-off of Lehman, shares in which will be traded on the New York Stock
Exchange, will create an investment bank which had post-tax income last year
of Dollars 376m and which would be valued at around Dollars 3.5bn, if the
stock market values it in a similar way to its rivals.
Explaining the reason not to float Lehman, Mr Harvey Golub, chairman and
chief executive of American Express, said the deal announced yesterday would
give the greatest value to the group's shareholders. A flotation of Lehman,
raising additional capital, would have attracted a tax charge on the
spin-off, he said. Also, American Express has the cash resources to
recapitalise the company without needing to tap the public markets, Mr Golub
said.
Under the terms of the deal, American Express is to put in Dollars 890m to
buy common stock in Lehman, as well as preference share capital of Dollars
200m. All the shares in the group will be distributed to American Express
shareholders, leaving the credit card group with only an interest in
Lehman's profits, if they exceed a set level in future years.
</TEXT>
