<PROFILE>_AN-EAYDAADPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940125
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: British Aerospace
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Talks between British Aerospace and Honda over the ownership of Rover might
seem a little odd at this stage of the business cycle. After all, Rover has
had to invest in new models - most recently the Rover 600 - and work hard to
cut working capital in order to get through the recession. Since Rover is
now gaining market share, should BAe not sit back and reap the benefits of
the hard work?
If BAe were free of any other constraints that might be true. But the
capital intensive nature of the motor industry means that companies are
rarely far away from the demands of new model development. While Rover
should begin to swing into profit, substantial cash generation to fund other
BAe projects may remain merely a nice idea. Meanwhile, Rover's working
capital requirements remain significant. This far, Honda has had the comfort
of a 20 per cent equity holding without having to cover any of Rover's
financing costs. An agreement on closer co-operation which involved Honda
sharing that burden would free up some of BAe's capital for use in other
parts of the business. If that were accompanied by a sale of Rover equity to
Honda at above book value it would also help underpin BAe's balance sheet.
That may be particularly useful at a time when BAe may wish to make
provisions against leases on its turboprop aircraft leases.
Honda too has reasons to pursue discussions. Gradually closer links between
manufacturers is part of the Japanese way of business. And cementing the two
companies more tightly would help Honda shut out a potential European
competitor.
</TEXT>
