<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: The capacity to recover
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturing industry could hardly be doing better, according to the CBI.
Demand is growing, albeit slowly. Export prospects have taken only a limited
knock from sterling's rise against the D-Mark. The strength of the US
economy helps, especially since sterling is weaker against the dollar than
when the last survey was taken. But export optimism also reflects the
steepest fall in unit costs since 1958 which is helping to boost margins
despite weak price rises.
Less clear is the extent to which cost cutting has resulted in capacity
being scrapped. A striking feature of the survey is the speed with which
capacity use has risen. Only 57 per cent of respondents are now operating
below capacity compared with 73 per cent a year ago. One reason could be
that the official figures understate the true level of output and demand,
but that sits badly with weak prices. Another may be that a slimmed-down
capacity is being used more efficiently. Operational gearing would then be
mainly responsible for the downward pressure on costs.
Capacity use cannot continue to grow at this rate without running up against
constraints. Though not an immediate problem, it would be comforting to see
stronger evidence of investment growth. The survey suggests most new
investment is still designed to improve efficiency rather than add capacity.
Worry about inadequate return is a deterrent. That could be because real
rates of interest are still too high. But many managers may still not have
adjusted expectations of nominal return to the new low inflation
environment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
