<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Yeltsin criticises Chernomyrdin for 'mistakes' over
government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president, yesterday reproached Mr Victor
Chernomyrdin, his prime minister, for 'mistakes' in forming his government
and rejected the resignation of Mr Boris Fyodorov as finance minister.
Mr Fyodorov, who had been asked at the weekend to stay on by an apparently
chastened Mr Chernomyrdin, was holding out for the dismissal of Mr Victor
Gerashchenko as central bank chairman before he would agree to remain in the
cabinet.
While Mr Yeltsin wants to keep his reputation as a reformist intact, Mr
Chernomyrdin, stung by the international outcry over his plans to 'correct'
reforms and let Mr Fyodorov go, has dismissed the backlash as being whipped
up against him.
Mr Alexander Shokhin, his new economics minister, went further, saying a
press campaign aimed to topple Mr Chernomyrdin by the spring.
Meanwhile, Professor Jeffrey Sachs, the most vocal foreign adviser to the
Russian government until his resignation last week, blamed the International
Monetary Fund for not disbursing enough funds to support reformers. He said
the Fund's chief, Mr Michel Camdessus, should quit.
In Washington, Mr Strobe Talbott, special adviser on the former Soviet Union
to Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, warned the new Russian
government that foreign aid would remain closely linked to economic reform.
'Gradual reform is a prescription for hyperinflation and economic collapse,'
Mr Talbott added, while warning that the US must not expect results
overnight.
Although the Russian president did not see Mr Fyodorov as expected
yesterday, Mr Sergei Alexashenko, the deputy finance minister, said the two
men might meet today.
Mr Fyodorov instead met Mr Vladimir Shcherbakov, the man who is being
considered by Mr Chernomyrdin as his replacement at the finance ministry.
Mr Shcherbakov, who now runs a Russian investment fund, belonged to the last
Soviet government which tried to depose President Mikhail Gorbachev. 'He
will accept any spending decisions. He will be a decoration,' said Mr
Alexashenko.
Mr Yeltsin's spokesman gave no details of the 'mistakes' for which the
president had berated his premier. But one possible compromise is that Mr
Fyodorov might be offered a vacant post as a first deputy prime minister.
But the position of number two or three in the government would still leave
unsatisfied Mr Fyodorov's demand for what he calls 'the scalp' of Mr
Gerashchenko, whom he has accused of 'provocations' at the central bank to
undermine his attempts to stabilise Russia's finances.
In response to a plea from Mr Anatoly Chubais, the other senior reformer in
the Russian government, for the sacking of the central bank governor, Mr
Yeltsin is said to have replied yesterday that the time was not right. 'Let
him make another mistake,' Mr Yeltsin was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
