<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Observer: Back to basics
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Funny how the big jobs in Swedish business are suddenly being handed out to
grey unknowns. Volvo's Pehr Gyllenhammar has been replaced by ABB's
Bert-Olof Svanholm and now Ericsson's Jan Stenberg has stepped into Jan
Carlzon's old slot at Scandinavian Airlines Systems. A couple of less
flamboyant figures would be hard to imagine.
Stenberg, a low-key business executive, has spent his entire career at the
telecommunications group and Svanholm has also been plucked from the heart
of Swedish industry. But different times require different types. Carlzon
was a super salesman who never got a proper grip on SAS's costs while
Gyllenhammer's grand visions rarely seemed to pay
off.
The challenge now is to ensure that the two companies can survive long-term
after the collapse of their ambitious merger plans. All the signs are that
SAS will concentrate on its core airline and Volvo on cars and trucks.
The new faces at the top of SAS and Volvo may be rather grey but the
appointments are a belated recognition that both SAS and Volvo are finally
going to have to swallow some of the unappetising medicine already downed by
their counterparts elsewhere in Swedish industry.
</TEXT>
