<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Observer: Tongue-tied in Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Poor old Gunter Baer. The secretary-general of the European central bank
governors' committee was thought to have sewn up the director-general's job
at the European Monetary Institute. His committee had carried out most of
the functions now transferred to the EMI and everyone seemed to think that
he had acquitted himself perfectly well in the old job.
But Baer has now fallen prey to a familiar problem for international job
hunters. In return for Frankfurt getting the EMI, France gets to tighten its
iron grip on the international financial jobs which matter. Robert Raymond,
a senior Bank of France official, will be nodded through as the EMI's
director-general at next month's council meeting in Basle.
In his early 60s, Raymond is a distinguished former head of research at the
French central bank and currently in charge of its credit department. Hence
no one doubts his ability  - and his advanced years could save the European
taxpayer big redundancy payments in an institution that is due to be
abolished if and when Europe adopts economic and monetary union.
However, the job is supposed to be a hands-on affair that could involve,
among other things, a good deal of negotiation with local worthies. Pity
Raymond can't speak the lingo.
</TEXT>
