<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Leading Article: Right road for spending
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government has been deservedly hoist on the low taxation petard
with which it undermined the Labour party at the general election. Yet the
debate, however entertaining, is not illuminating. If taxes are to be
significantly lower, public spending must also be reduced. But such a
reduction would require radicalism, something that looks unlikely from the
government and almost inconceivable from the opposition.
The government's rhetoric about the need to control public spending has not
prevented the share of general government spending in gross domestic product
from returning to where it was when Mrs Thatcher took office. At 45 per cent
of GDP in 1993-94 the ratio is, in fact, one percentage point higher than in
1978-79. This does not mean that British governments have had no success in
controlling spending: at comparable periods of the economic cycle the ratio
was still higher, at 49 1/4 per cent in 1975-76 and 47 1/2 per cent in
1982-93. It does mean its success has been limited.
Success has been particularly limited in recent years. Between 1988-89 and
1993-94, general government spending will have grown by 16.1 per cent in
real terms, while GDP will have risen by a mere 1.3 per cent. Against that
background, the only alternative to higher taxes would have been still
higher borrowing, which would mean yet higher taxes in future. The
government was right to prevent that outcome, however painful the
consequences.
Higher ratio
Against the international background, the government's achievement is not
even that poor. Last December's Economic Outlook showed that every OECD
member state had a higher ratio of government spending to GDP in 1993 than
in 1979. The UK's ratio is even below the unweighted average, which stood at
51.2 per cent in 1993.
Only three OECD countries - Switzerland, Japan and the United States - have
ratios below 40 per cent. Two countries - Denmark and Sweden - have ratios
above 60 per cent, with Sweden teetering on 73.5 per cent. In between lie
the great majority. Most European countries have ratios above 50 per cent,
the exceptions being Ireland, Spain and the UK. Germany (50.8 per cent),
France (54.2 per cent) and Italy (54.8 per cent) all bear a somewhat higher
burden than the UK (47 per cent in these figures).
The OECD also shows where the differences arise. Compared with the UK, for
example, the US spends far less of its GDP on publicly provided health and
housing. Compared with the UK, Japan spends far less on defence and income
transfers. Again compared with the UK, Germany spends far more on income
transfers, which is still truer of other northern European welfare states.
Core function
Income transfers have, in fact, become the core function of the European
state, accounting for 26.8 per cent of GDP in Sweden in 1990, 23 per cent in
Denmark, 18.5 per cent in Germany, but 13.4 per cent in the UK, 11.9 per
cent in the US and only 7.8 per cent in Japan. In European welfare states,
provision of public goods and economic services, the classic functions of
the public sector, accounts for a far smaller share of GDP than transfers.
In the UK, by comparison, the two elements are equivalent in size.
Nevertheless, the UK's situation is not so different from that of other
European states. What the Department of Social Security in a recent pamphlet
calls 'social protection' (which includes health), accounted for 26 per cent
of GDP in the European Union in 1990. At 23 per cent, the UK's ratio is
again below the European average, but not wildly so. The world's top 10
spenders on social protection are European states and all face spiralling
costs.
The European states are on a treadmill. High public spending necessitates
high taxes which undermine incentives and exacerbate poverty traps. These,
in turn, lead to still higher unemployment and yet higher public spending.
If they are to get off the treadmill, they will have to be radical. But
radicalism is politically risky. The alternatives include more precisely
drawn priorities, greater reliance on private provision and more extensive
use of charges. Failing such radicalism from their governments, all European
electorates will continue to grumble about worsening services and, of
course, higher taxes.
</TEXT>
