<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At their best Peter Greenaway's films - The Draughtsman's Contract, The
Belly Of An Architect - are as good as Bunuel's and better than Jean Luc
Godard's. The trouble is that, like his Spanish and French precursors,
Greenaway tends towards not only the weird but the studiously obscure. Full
of visual interest, cleverly used music, and splendid performances (all
depending very much on the director) his work too often makes you want to
hold his head under water until he explains what he's getting at.
This applies less than usual in his modern-day revenge tragedy The Cook, The
Thief, His Wife And Her Lover, which gets its first television showing today
(10.30 C4). It stars Michael Gambon as a violent crook who lords it in his
own restaurant while his wife (Helen Mirren) has it away in the loo with
another customer.
BBC2's series, Assignment, investigates the 'Yardies", violent West Indian
criminals who operate in the US and London (7.45 BBC2). Desmond Lynam
presents a new 'infotainment' series: How Do They Do That? (8.00 BBC1).
