<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Business and the Law: When waste is not wanted - Germany's
recycling legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL ROSE and DAVID PERCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Germany has no difficulty in persuading companies to recycle packaging -
they have to do so, by law. The scale of German recycling, however, has
caused problems for other countries in Europe.
By generating large surpluses of recyclable materials, which the German
market cannot absorb, it is cheaper for recyclers to obtain waste paper and
plastics from Germany than to collect them locally.
The surpluses have also caused domestic problems for Germany: the
private-sector organisation that collects the materials has run into
financial trouble as the costs of recycling escalate.
The regulation that helped to create this situation was the 1991 Packaging
Ordinance; the government proposes to amend this around March. The latest
draft provides for a relaxation in recycling targets and allows a limited
amount of the surpluses to be incinerated to recover their energy content.
However, most of the essentials of the ordinance would remain unchanged.
The ordinance compels German producers of packaging waste to take it back
for reuse or material recycling. Incineration for energy recovery is
currently not allowed. Manufacturers, fillers, wholesalers and retailers
must take back packaging from the link below them in the chain, beginning
with the retailer, who must take it back from the consumer.
For transit packaging, the new text softens the demand for material
recycling - it will only be required where 'technically possible' and 'the
additional costs . . . are not unreasonable in comparison with other
recycling processes'. This is apparently left to the holder's judgment.
This relaxation should help waste managers who take on the collection and
recycling duties of their customers and seek an outlet through energy
incineration. However, the revised ordinance needs to make the cost
comparison clearer.
In theory the take-back rule also applies to sales packaging. In practice,
retailers avoid turning their shops into rubbish dumps by belonging to a
government-approved independent collection and separation system, which
meets set collection and recycling targets.
This system is run by Duales System Deutschland, which charges packaged
goods producers and importers a fee for the right to display a 'green spot'
on their packaging - a symbol that tells the retailer it will not have to
take back that packaging from customers. Householders separate their
packaging waste, to be collected and passed to reprocessors without charge.
DSD's fee operates as a subsidy, financing collection and separation of
unlimited quantities of packaging waste.
This charge becomes the waste manager's sole source of profit.
The new text for the ordinance alters the current Dual System's targets. At
the moment, targets cover, first, quantities collected, and second, amounts
sorted, of suitable quality material. The new text abandons collection
targets under such a Dual System, and fixes minimum recycling rates as a
percentage of total packaging marketed.
The percentages (by weight, see table) are lower under the proposed
amendment, and instead of being brought in through two stages, there are
three.
In the ordinance the sorting targets are expressed as a percentage of
packaging collected, so the more that is collected, the more has to be
sorted. The minimum recycling rate is effectively the collection percentage
multiplied by the sorting percentage.
With the exception of glass, all targets for the first stage are higher.
However, they fall from January 1 1996, the most significant reduction being
for the following three-year period to January 1 1998. For plastics, half
the minimum target must be met by techniques ensuring new use through
melting, dissolving or turning into pellets.
The new text will permit energy incineration once collection targets are
achieved. Failing this, excess materials must be sent to the public
authority for incineration as commercial waste.
In 1992, the Federal Cartel Office ruled against any extension of DSD's
activities to industrial waste. The Dual System therefore applies only to
collections from households, cafes, bars and small businesses.
A companion measure, the Marking Ordinance, would apply from July 1 1995,
after clearance by the European Commission. This would require all packaging
to be marked with the word Mehrweg (multi-trip, or reused several times) or
Einweg (one-trip). Packaging manufacturers must indicate Stofflich
Verwertbar (recyclable), Verwertbar (if recoverable in another way) or Nicht
Verwertbar (non-recoverable). Polymers must be listed separately.
For one-trip packaging, an indication must be given on the pack of the
estimated disposal cost. This, however, could mislead the consumer, who does
not have full information about the packaging's cost-effectiveness.
Another country with recycling legislation is France. In 1992 it passed a
decree for household packaging waste under which, as in Germany, the
producer must either take it back or pass responsibility to a state-approved
organisation and pay for an identifying logo.
However, the French manage to avoid some of the pitfalls of German
legislation, even in its amended form. Thus France makes membership of a
government-approved collection scheme a legal requirement for fillers and
importers, rather than relying, as Germany does, on retailers to police the
system.
To keep supply and demand roughly in balance, France gives clean energy
incineration equal status with recycling. Also commitments from sectoral
recycling organisations predetermine collection and separation volumes of
the local authorities.
French local authorities are responsible for collection, and 'green spot'
licence fees are used to help them develop their systems. Germany still
follows the expensive, inefficient line of insisting on independent
recycling.
France is preparing a separate law for industrial and commercial waste which
makes maximum use of existing collection systems, an example that Germany
should follow. And in contrast to Germany's rigid targets, France does not
prescribe targets by legislation but imposes them through the machinery for
licensing the organising agency. This allows flexibility.
Germany's recycling targets are much higher than the maximum figures in the
draft European Union Packaging Directive. The directive allows member states
to set higher targets if the Commission confirms that they avoid internal
market distortions and do not hinder compliance by other member states.
Germany opposes this condition and, if challenged, will invoke article
100(a)(4) of the Treaty of Rome, which permits national environmental
protection measures after a harmonisation measure is passed. Arguably, the
European Court of Justice in Luxembourg should rule that that this refers to
the EU environment as a whole rather than Germany's national environment.
Michael Rose is a partner of City solicitors S. J. Berwin &amp; Co and David
Perchard is head of Perchards, European affairs consultants
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
RECYCLING IN GERMANY
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Targets               From      From      From
                    1.1.93    1.1.96    1.1.98
                  per cent  per cent  per cent
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Glass                   40        70        70
Tinplate                30        70        70
Aluminium               20        70        70
Paper/board             20        50        60
Plastics                10        50        60
Board composites        10        50        60
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
