<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Survey of International Legal Services (5): Shift to client
power puts curb on costs - Diana Bentley investigates attitudes to
alternative billing and value for money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANA BENTLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Times change. In the ebullient 1980s large legal fees often merged
imperceptibly into total transaction costs and were accepted with the
optimism and confidence which characterised most of the decade.
But the grim realities of the recession have fostered new attitudes to
lawyers' remuneration, and established practices unlikely to be discarded
even in improved economic conditions.
'There has definitely been a shift in power to the client,' says John de
Forte of de Forte Associates, consultants to the profession. 'The pressure
on costs which started in other fields like auditing really predated the
recession - the growth in the 1980s intensified competition and caused the
breakdown of loyalty to advisers but the recession has accelerated the
changes,' he says.
Methods of costing which were considered common by late 1993 show a marked
difference from the 1980s. They reflect the flexibility and control now
considered to be important elements in managing legal services. It is
incumbent on in-house lawyers especially to monitor and reduce legal costs.
Most recent trends indicate that lawyers and clients have increased the
efficiency and reduced the cost of the delivery of legal services, but Mr de
Forte believes that new practices, are not cyclical, but structural, and
here to stay.
While most commercial and litigation work has traditionally been costed on
an hourly fee basis, 'Generally there is now a disenchantment with hourly
rates,' says Derham O'Neill of Clifford Chance, London. Hourly rates for
large City firms can average Pounds 260 for a partner, Pounds 140 for an
assistant; or Pounds 170 and Pounds 100 respectively in the provinces.
'Regional firms have done well recently, often because of their lower hourly
rates,' notes Mr de Forte.
Rates now are often agreed before work is begun, and are subject to
negotiation. Despite the fact that rates for partners or senior lawyers may
vary within a firm to reflect seniority or the complexity of work, many
clients, (including government bodies) prefer to strike one rate for all
partners for simplicity, and similarly for different levels of support
staff.
The practice of calling for competitive quotes from candidates for work has
had a greater impact. This has become commonplace, although many firms
remain uncomfortable with the practice. 'Tendering has always been used -
especially by government bodies, but its use has been extended recently,'
explains Mr O'Neill.
The stimulus has been, largely, dissatisfaction with high fees and the
uncertainty which purely hourly costing causes. Though tendering may be
dispensed with where highly specialised skills are required, it is
established as a sensible means of selecting legal services where a range of
firms provide equal expertise and experience.
But price is not, and should not always be, the deciding factor in
selection. Other key questions, says John de Forte, are how the firm will
prevent 'over-lawyering', and guarantee the proper relationship between the
matter and the expertise it requires. 'Clients are increasingly keen to get
value for money,' says Derham O'Neill. 'That can mean the selection of fewer
firms, but ones which can deliver appropriate quality - whether for
specialised or routine work.'
Diana Miller, Legal &amp; General group legal services manager, agrees. 'The
quality of the advice is always paramount and in-house counsel are well
placed to judge it, but we also consider closely the services we want, and
generally need service that is cost effective,' she says.
Another marked trend is the move to fixed fees, or fees agreed for the whole
job, but they also present problems for firms: 'Clients like fixed fees -
lawyers find them difficult,' says Derham O'Neill.
While lawyers' experience of the average relevant transaction can suggest
the appropriate fee, external factors can invalidate estimates causing
problems for clients and lawyers. 'Lawyers need to get better at developing
fuller specifications on what is and what is not covered by the fee,' Mr
O'Neill adds.
For a proper assessment of value for money, clients often need more
information on what the fee covers. Usually, distribution and use of
resources is critical. The awkward question remains: who bears the
additional cost where the fixed fee is understated, but capping (the
practice by which the firm agrees to take the risk on the override) is not
yet common in the UK.
On top of hourly rates, premium billing - or the addition of a lump sum to
reflect the complexity of the case and degree of responsibility - was common
in the 1980s, but Diana Miller says that premiums are now used less; the
market for legal services is more competitive, and it is more usual for
clients to expect a discount if for some reason the matter does not proceed,
or is unsuccessful.
For companies rationalising their legal services and able to provide regular
work of a predictable type, volume discounts can secure efficient services -
their growth is a sign of more flexible billing practices. Even given these
charges, the profession can look for no comfort from its most senior
members.
As recently as October 1993, in an address to the Bar's annual conference,
Lord Taylor of Gosforth, the Lord Chief Justice, attacked the fees charged
in particular to large corporate clients by solicitors and barristers in
contentious matters which, he said, were often out of all proportion to a
reasonable rate for the job.
Elsewhere, particularly in the US, where excessive billing has fostered the
growth of legal cost audit services, the way in which lawyers charge is
similarly being scrutinised. But in the US, too, options for charging are
greater.
Contingency fees for litigation have long been permitted in the US. Banned
in England as contrary to public policy, they are not permitted, either, in
civil law jurisdictions such as Germany, France and Belgium. Despite
arguments that they improve access to legal remedies, recent utterances from
Lord Taylor and others who fear they may boost speculative litigation,
suggest that contingency fees are unlikely to be approved in England.
But some formal changes are occurring. By this spring, a conditional fee
system approved by the Lord Chancellor's department will be permitted, under
which a lawyer may charge an 'uplift' or percentage of the normal fee where
the action is successful, but such fees will be restricted to personal
injury and insolvency cases.
The trend towards more efficient delivery of legal services, with manning as
an important aspect of this, should continue. Mr O'Neill expects that there
will be increased pressure to appoint smaller teams on matters involving
more multi-skilled lawyers.
For law firms, this will require broader training and an emphasis on highly
organised integrated delivery of services to reduce client costs. 'What
clients want is transparency and a clear idea about how work will be handled
and by whom,' he says.
Ms Miller of Legal &amp; General agrees. 'Legal fees are the same as any cost in
a business - suppliers of services can't bill indiscriminately, but need to
provide full information of how they charge and demonstrate they are cost
effective.'
Monitoring of costs is another area where improvements could be made to
ensure cost effectiveness, John de Forte says. Law firms need to provide
information in advance, details of current billing to date, work in progress
and anticipated overall fees compared to budget.
'Regular billing is an increasing trend and a good one which requires
discipline,' Derham O'Neill remarks. Overall, Mr de Forte says, controlling
costs should be just be one aspect of how you manage the whole relationship.
