<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Survey of International Legal Services (6): Mediation is
quicker and cheaper - The UK is one of several countries following the US in
alternative dispute resolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANA BENTLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Conflict is eternal,' notes Tony Willis, managing partner for litigation at
Clifford Chance - a good vantage point from which to make the observation.
But as impatience with the problems of litigation mounts, it is not
surprising that the UK is following the US lead in embracing alternative
dispute resolution (ADR) as a means of resolving contentious matters.
'Essentially, the heavy costs, delays, uncertainties and unwieldy processes
of litigation common to all common law countries are the main reasons for
people turning to ADR,' says Professor Karl Mackie, chief executive of the
Centre for Dispute Resolution (CEDR) in London. As he explains, 'the
evolving business culture characterised by rapid change, emphasis on fast
responses and getting value for money set against a Dickensian legal system
make a powerful cocktail for change.'
Mr Willis, who is himself experienced in ADR, confirms that the problems of
litigation are now often unacceptable to clients and advisers.
While in the US the term ADR usually includes binding arbitration, in the UK
it normally refers to non-adjudicatory techniques. 'For commercial
disputes,' observes Professor Mackie, 'mediation, which bears a close
resemblance to negotiation, is overwhelmingly the most popular ADR form in
the UK.'
Nevertheless, other techniques may be suitable for particular disputes.
Executive tribunals - called mini-trials in the US, and more formal in
nature - involve case appraisal by executive evaluators and a neutral
chairman; the judicial appraisal scheme launched recently by CEDR, similar
to the US 'rent-a-judge' system, provides retired judges and lawyers to
assess the legal merits of a case and to narrow the issues for those
considering litigation.
Though unsuitable in some cases, for example, where injunctive relief is
required, ADR generally offers many advantages over litigation, including a
wider range of solutions, a better control of risk and confidentiality.
Another significant benefit, says Roger Myddelton, Grand Metropolitan's
group legal director, is that ADR can help preserve the commercial
relationship because it need not involve allocations of fault. 'The process
looks forwards rather than backwards.'
But it is in the cost area where ADR's benefits are especially tantalising.
'For a major matter in the commercial court, costs can run into millions of
pounds,' says Mr Willis.
Costs at CEDR are based on the amount in dispute and range from several
hundred to over a thousand pounds a day, depending on the amount in dispute.
Most mediations, however, settle in one to three days: a recent
CEDR-arranged mediation of a dispute involving Pounds 27m, set for a 12-week
hearing, lasted just one day.
In the US, as in England, about 90-95 per cent of filed cases are resolved
before trial, so there is often little reason for companies not to try ADR
early on. But ADR is a more recent phenomenon in the UK than in the US.
Since its launch in 1990, CEDR has had some 360 cases, worth approximately
Pounds 1.5bn, referred to it, and mediation has a 90-95 per cent success
rate. 'After some initial reluctance ADR's growth rate shows a steep
increase,' says Professor Mackie. 'The influence of a skilled trained
mediator means it is much more powerful than private negotiation.'
The recent experience of Colin Gilbert, group legal director of Eurocopy,
bears this out. CEDR arranged a mediation for the company's Pounds 300,000
dispute involving a client and three leasing companies. The trigger to try
ADR was the desire to preserve the client relationship. Mr Gilbert says: 'I
thought there was little common ground, but I was astounded.'
The matter was resolved in just one day, with the parties representing
themselves. Costs were about Pounds 1,000 each. Mr Gilbert is experienced in
litigation; his estimate of legal costs on the matter was about Pounds
40,000 each. Surviving the experience successfully has cemented the
relationship between the parties, he says.
Most CEDR cases are domestic, but its international referrals are growing -
a consequence of the growth of international trade, the complexities of
cross-border litigation and the growing recognition of ADR's value.
Elsewhere, the trend is similar. Sydney is the home of the Australian
Commercial Disputes Centre, established with government backing in 1986. New
York has one of the oldest ADR centres: the Centre for Public Resources
(CPR). Interest is growing elsewhere. CEDR has recently received a European
Commission grant to consult on the development of ADR in continental Europe.
Yet despite the increasing interest in ADR among the private sector, and the
high settlement rates in litigation, courts in England until now have
provided no incentives to settlement. As Mr Willis of Clifford Chance points
out, while in Germany and France judges may intervene to influence the
parties to settle cases, in England they do not do so. 'But ADR can provide
the missing element,' he says. It may now do so.
Aware of public dissatisfaction with litigation, legal regulators are
beginning to recognise ADR.
The commercial court has now established a court-annexed ADR scheme,
prompted by the recommendations of the 1993 Heilbron Report on the civil
courts (which was damning in its findings). Legal advisers to court
litigants must ensure that parties are informed of the most cost-effective
means of resolving particular issues and disputes.
The commercial court clerk keeps a list of ADR services. This includes
numerous former commercial court judges and ADR bodies such as CEDR.
Prof Mackie notes that while the Lord Chancellor's department has expressed
an interest in ADR, no formal approach for discussions on the subject has
been made to CEDR.
Experts say that parties must be willing to seek an agreed solution for ADR
to be effective - but the spectre of full litigation is a spur. 'ADR nearly
always works better in conjunction with traditional means of adjudicative
dispute resolution, or at least with their availability,' says Mr Willis.
'ADR is not a panacea, and the sometimes arduous disciplines it requires
need to be learnt.'
While the take-up rate of ADR in England has been faster than in the US, Mr
Willis believes that the spread of business people with a detailed knowledge
of the area remains thin. Top management is likely to be most interested,
given its responsibilities, although the US practice of some chief
executives pledging to endeavour to resolve disputes by ADR may not take off
so soon in the UK.
Still, Mr Willis says that in many cases ADR presents a better solution in
resolving disputes and there is growing experience in the field. Education
and familiarity remain the key. 'People's scepticism is usually overcome
when they appreciate the system's common sense, simplicity and
effectiveness,' says Professor Mackie.
In-house lawyers have long seen effective dispute management as important to
their role. GrandMet's Mr Myddelton fosters ADR.
Of those in private practice, Professor Mackie says, 'lawyers have a
constructive role to play in ADR but some may feel there is no financial
incentive to encourage its use, so clients also need to be more assertive
with legal advisers.'
Nevertheless, he is optimistic. 'As lawyers become more experienced in ADR
they will develop a better sense of how it can contribute to their practice.
We are on the verge of a big growth in ADR.'
</TEXT>
