<PROFILE>_AN-EAYDAACIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940125
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Survey of International Legal Services (3): Marriages of
convenience - A look at cross-border corporate joint ventures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANA BENTLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like marriages of convenience, joint ventures owe more to the parties'
perception of the relationships' worldly benefits than to more altruistic
motives.
But while joint ventures are of increasing importance in the European Union
for sound business reasons, they also involve a difficult balancing act for
regulators - especially for the EU, as it seeks to reconcile its need to
achieve the single market with its desire to maintain effective EU
competition.
Despite the recession, the number of 1991-1992 joint ventures declined more
slowly than takeovers and mergers in the EU. They also have a predominantly
cross-border character.
Community and international operations accounted for 72 per cent of total
joint ventures in 1991-1992. French firms predominated in joint venture
activity, followed by Germany and then UK companies - but they are also a
popular method by which Japanese and US firms increase their growth in
Europe.
Overall, the national, EU and international joint ventures across 12
industry sectors doubled in the five years to 1990. Increases in the
chemical, electrical and automotive industries were most pronounced.
Political factors have stimulated international trading. 'The advent of the
EU single market and the opening up of the former Soviet Union, China and
Eastern Europe to western and other investors, have contributed to the
recent increase in cross-border joint ventures,' says Jim Wheaton of
Clifford Chance, the London law firm.
But, given heightened trading opportunities, what is making joint ventures
so alluring? 'A common reason for engaging in joint ventures is to enter new
markets,' Mr Wheaton says, 'and the indications are that this trend is
rapidly increasing.'
Local knowledge, facilities, labour and customers can be provided through
local venture partners. 'Making a product in your own market and sending it
out into the world is increasingly under challenge,' says Brian
Woods-Scawen, corporate finance partner of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, accountants.
'Companies need to understand markets from the inside, and joint ventures
also permit greater control than employing local agents and distributors.'
Accelerated technological change has often forced huge investment in
research and development. Organisational size has become critical in
corporate competitiveness, and so has the need for rationalisation and
restructuring. Fears of protectionism also prompt local alliances. Now, even
the biggest companies may lack time and talent for solo efforts. Joint
efforts also reduce risk.
'Administratively, joint ventures are more complicated, but constraints in
time, money, manpower and knowledge are all factors in considering joint
ventures,' says Wolfgang Schneider, assistant general counsel at Ford
Europe. Ford's alliances cover a spectrum of different aspects of the
business, from the production of components to the manufacture of a whole
vehicle.
'Joint ventures are usually prompted by numerous factors, but the percentage
of each factor varies with each case,' says Mr Woods-Scawen, 'and
understanding these reasons and choice of partner is often more important
than the precise structure.'
Despite the popularity of joint ventures, in the EU there are attendant
regulatory hurdles involving competition law. The EU's competition policy is
central to its aims, but as the EU is keen to foster efficiency gains in EU
industry, the past four years have seen an improvement in regulatory
treatment in the area.
Despite the level of merger activity, it was only with the Merger Regulation
of 1989 that specific EU merger control appeared. Mergers exceeding
threshold amounts of corporate turnovers are subject to compulsory
prenotification, but notifications must be dealt with rapidly and under the
'one-stop shop' principle.
Qualifying mergers are considered at EU level and do not usually involve
national authorities. The European Commission must decide within a month if
the transaction is acceptable. If it gives rise to serious doubts about its
competitive effect, it will be subject to a a detailed investigation for up
to four months. The record of approvals, however, is good. About 90 per cent
of transactions are approved at the first stage, after which they may be
approved subject to conditions.
Aligned to the merger policy, and closely affected by it, is EU policy on
joint ventures. EU competition law, however, differentiates between
concentrative and co-operative joint ventures. If the venture is
concentrative and threshold provisions of the Merger Regulation are met, the
venture must be notified under the Merger Regulation - and attracts the
one-stop treatment.
Co-operative joint ventures are less fortunate. Outside the scope of the
Merger Regulation they are assessed under the Rome Treaty rules on
anti-competitive agreements and abuse of monopoly power. The EU's
jurisdiction is not exclusive, and transactions may be examined as well by
relevant national authorities - a time-consuming process with uncertain
results.
'There is a crucial difference of treatment of the two forms of joint
venture,' says Michael Reynolds of Allen &amp; Overy's Brussels office, 'and it
is complicated by the fact that joint ventures take many forms.'
Jointly owned companies are the most popular. But partners may only put part
of their businesses into a new entity, contributions may be of a different
nature, and many also take place between traditional rivals.
A venture is considered concentrative if it performs, on a lasting basis,
all the functions of an autonomous economic entity. It is considered
co-operative in nature if it does not constitute such an entity - or if,
although it does constitute such an entity, it gives rise to co-ordination
of competitive behaviour by the parents in relation to each other or in
relation to the joint venture.
Jim Wheaton says: 'Leave parents with some involvement in the market, even
downstream or upstream, and there is a risk that there will be some
restraint on competition between parents or that there will be an impact on
third parties.'
It was the level of joint venture activity which made EU authorities
reassess their procedures. 'The success of the EU Merger Regulation
highlighted the failure of the commission to set up a satisfactory mechanism
to appraise co-operative joint ventures, Mr Wheaton adds.
Now the EC has improved its treatment of these alliances; from January 1993
the commission has been obliged to indicate - within two months of a
co-operative venture notification - whether it believes the venture is
compatible with EU competition laws or gives rise to serious doubts, and
requires further examination.
The EC's decision, however, is not binding as it is in relation to mergers.
Nonetheless, at national level, little progress is being made. Clearance is
needed under the competition laws of individual member states for
co-operative joint ventures. Because member states laws differ, applications
need to be tailored to their individual requirements. National rules on when
these laws apply also vary; in some, it is necessary to have a party with an
office in the state but in others sales only are required.
National authorities, experts say, can be tougher than the EC, as they are
looking at their own national markets rather than at the EU or the
international picture. The necessity for national appraisal, Michael
Reynolds says, 'is often a tortuous, fairly unpredictable route. One
national authority alone can hold you up.' Led by the OECD, there is some
talk of the need to harmonise national rules, but little progress is
apparent.
However, those states which have not had competition laws until recently,
such as Italy and Spain, have modelled their laws on EU laws. But Germany
and the UK have long had quite distinct competition laws. Attempts to
harmonise them may prove difficult.
While the distinction between co-operative and concentrative joint ventures
is often a fine one, differences in regulatory treatment remain significant.
But experts claim there is scope for structuring deals to ensure that they
are within the merger provisions - so the earlier the advice is sought, the
better. The setting up of a jointly owned company with its own finance and
sales force, making it an autonomous entity so that the parents withdraw
permanently from the market, is akin to merger - and unlikely to restrain
competition between parents.
A third party can be introduced to ensure that the deal meets merger control
thresholds. 'Clients are often willing to alter the commercial structure to
some extent to get different regulatory treatment,' says Mr Reynolds.
Still, companies understand the remaining hazards of the present regimes.
'The EU authorities have made an appreciable effort, involving self-imposed
disciplines, to improve the treatment of mergers and joint ventures,' says
Wolfgang Schneider of Ford. But he believes an even clearer framework could
be sought.
