<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / CBI optimistic on business trends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Confederation of British Industry survey yesterday painted a more
optimistic picture of business trends than last week's report from the
British Chambers of Commerce.
The CBI was unabashed by the discrepancy. It pointed out that most of its
replies were received after the start of January; the British Chambers of
Commerce survey was carried out between November 26 and December 17. The CBI
also said its report covered larger companies and included a wider range of
questions.
This does not account for all the discrepancies. Smaller companies, tied to
the fortunes of the domestic economy, seem to be performing better than
larger ones. This should have made the Chambers of Commerce survey, focused
on smaller companies, more optimistic than the CBI report.
An encouraging sign in the CBI survey is that orders and output are
increasing faster than forecast in the last report in October. Total new
orders grew at the strongest rate since January 1989, with a balance of plus
11 per cent experiencing an increase. That compares with just plus 5 per
cent expecting an increase in October. The trend also appears to be
strengthening, with plus 22 per cent - the highest figure since October 1988
 -expecting order growth to continue over the next four months.
The pound's recent strength does not appear to have had a substantial impact
on export orders. The balance of those experiencing an increase was plus 8
per cent while plus 18 per cent expect a rise over the next four months.
However, the percentage of those naming prices as the main constraint on
export demand rose to 56 per cent, from 52 per cent in October.
A balance of plus 9 per cent saw growth in manufacturing output over the
last four months, a slightly higher figure than in October. The CBI
forecasts that output will grow by 0.7 per cent in the first quarter of
1994, based on its survey figure showing a balance of plus 16 per cent
expecting an increase. Furthermore, the balance of companies intending to
increase spending on plant and machinery over the coming year was positive
for the first time since July 1989. More companies have cut domestic prices
than raised them over the last four months, and the same trend is true in
export prices. There is a strong balance of plus 12 per cent in favour of
increasing prices over the next four months.
Price pressures are being eased by companies' tight control on costs. Unit
costs fell faster than at any time since 1958, when the survey was first
conducted, with 12 per cent more companies reporting a fall in costs over
the past four months than an increase, and 5 per cent more expecting costs
to decline than to go up.
</TEXT>
