<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / A quest for the acceptable face of intervention: Andrew
Adonis weighs up the competitive edge of Michael Heseltine's aims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine's announcement of a forthcoming government white paper
on competitiveness heralds no dramatic policy shift. Instead, it looks set
to bring together recent public and private-sector initiatives, add a few
more, and release the package with the kind of bang that no-one in the
government but the trade and industry secretary seems able to create.
The new policy tone came nearly two years ago, when Mr Heseltine succeeded
Mr Peter Lilley at the Department of Trade and Industry. In practice, Mr
Heseltine is no more interventionist than his predecessor, but he is keener
to admit how much intervention takes place - and determined to focus state
resources on addressing weaknesses.
As he put it to a Commons committee last week: 'I have been a minister since
1970 . . . and I must tell you that all governments intervene all the time;
the only question is what form it takes.'
The backdrop to the white paper is deepening concern at the capacity even of
top-notch UK companies to compete, particularly against rising industries in
Asia.
A report last year by IBM Consulting Group, part of the US computing giant,
claimed from a study of 202 UK manufacturing sites that only 2 per cent were
world-class, although three-quarters believed they could match the best
international standards.
As a first step, Mr Heseltine has given improved export promotion a high
priority. He is 'signing up' ambassadors to a new approach. Where more than
one UK company is bidding for a state contract abroad, the government will
generally put its lobbying weight behind just one bid 'whereas before it
often just stood aside'.
Mr Heseltine is even expecting ambassadors and their staff to be available
for video-conference briefings with people gathered in new 'Business Links'
being established across the country. Electronics components producers in
Swindon should be able to ask, say, the British consul in Chicago about
developments in the US mid west's vehicle industry.
Spreading best practice is another key theme. Two months ago the
Confederation of British Industry launched a 'competitiveness forum' geared
to highlighting excellence in manufacturing industry and spreading the word.
Twenty companies have been designated so far; briefings by senior executives
and one-day 'best practice focus sessions' are being organised with the host
company vetting the guest list to avoid commercial sensitivities.
US practice is a strong influence, with its 'competitiveness councils' and
annual bench-marking.
So far, however, Mr Heseltine's initiatives have been more limited. To date
he has:
Split up the DTI's trade and exports division, with 80 named officials
responsible for each export market under a director-general of export
promotion.
Set up a competitiveness unit headed by Mr Bob Dobbie, which is working with
trade associations to 'benchmark' industrial sectors against their
counterparts abroad. The results, unpublished, are said to make depressing
reading.
Established 'Business Links' as local outlets for DTI services currently
handled by its nine regional offices, also tapping the resources of local
Chambers of Commerce and Training and Enterprise Councils. As yet only four
have been set up, the largest of which is in Birmingham. But the target is
200 within two years.
But how much conviction is there that the new structures will make a
difference? At last week's Commons trade and industry committee meeting, Mr
Heseltine was asked, from his experience as an entrepreneur in the 1960s,
what the government could have done to help him. 'Abolish the DTI,' came the
reply.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
