<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Pensions code sought by funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government should consider implementing regulatory reform of pension
schemes through codes of practice rather than legislation, the National
Association of Pension Funds, the industry trade association, said
yesterday.
The Department of Social Security has invited comment on proposals to reform
the regulatory regime for occupational pensions prepared by its Pensions Law
Review Committee chaired by Professor Roy Goode.
The association said legislation could be years away, while many elements of
the proposals could be in place by the autumn if there were a code of
conduct.
Mr David Morgan, chairman of the association's parliamentary committee,
said: 'In endorsing this robust new system and supporting most of the Goode
recommendations, we are concerned that uncertainty over the two years until
any new legislation could come into effect would make it difficult to plan
with confidence.'
The association conceded that codes of conduct were not legally enforceable,
but 'the Inland Revenue has worked with codes of conduct for years and try
breaking one of those'. It said that failure to comply with voluntary codes
of conduct should cost schemes their tax-exemption rights.
The association recognises that at least some of the elements of the Goode
Committee recommendations, such as the creation of a new pensions regulator,
will require primary legislation.
In its response to the report, the association urged changes in the most
crucial element of proposals for pension fund reform - the requirement that
all schemes meet a so-called minimum solvency requirement ensuring that they
could meet 90 per cent of all liabilities if they were suddenly wound up.
</TEXT>
