<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Cheerful Tories do their sums: The tide may be turning
against Labour in Birmingham for local elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Birmingham Conservatives look remarkably cheerful. Not for them the
discomfort of rhetorical twists on 'back to basics', paternal confessions
about love children, Iraq amnesia and allegations of gerrymandering. They
scent power.
The campaign for May's local elections in the UK's largest metropolitan
authority has already started. Mathematically, the Conservative position is
promising. The party needs a gain of four seats to break Labour control, a
gain of 10 to become the largest party on the city council and a gain of 16
to win overall control.
The party hopes for an election decided on local issues. One of the three
main priorities on the Conservative local election platform is what Mr
Bernard Zissman, the Tory leader, calls 'waste in the Birmingham council'.
Certainly Mrs Theresa Stewart, who came to the Labour leadership from the
left of the party, has had three difficult months. There have been rows, and
some have been serious, such as those about spending priorities and whether
more should be spent on education and less on prestige civil projects such
as the International Convention Centre. Some have been trivial, attracting
ridicule: for example, the accusation that the council tried to ban
Christmas by having Christmas lights without Christian symbols.
Labour tightened its grip on the council in 1990, but lost ground at the
last local election. At the 1992 elections, the Conservatives won 11 seats,
taking their total to 43. Labour was left with 61 and the Liberal Democrats
13, with one held by an independent.
This shifting political balance is not unknown in the city. 'Birmingham is
untypical in that, historically, there is an even balance between the
parties,' said Dr Carl Chinn, Birmingham University's community historian.
Labour has had a majority since 1984. Dr Chinn said: 'Labour has been in
control longer this time than the normal cycle of six to eight years. It
takes three or four years to build up the vote and then three or four years
to lose it again.'
So there are two contradictory trends. The cyclical trend favours the
Tories. However, disillusion with central government favours Labour on the
assumption that there is no surge of popularity for Mr John Major's
government over the next four months.
Mrs Stewart, who has been Labour leader of the council since last autumn,
relates control in Birmingham to control of the national government. 'The
real pattern in Birmingham is a vote against the government. The only break
was 1982 after the Falklands war.'
She dismissed Labour losses in 1992 because they happened just after the
general election. 'People were carried along on that tide, Labour people
were despondent,' she said. In fact, the Tories won local government seats
although they lost three parliamentary constituencies in the city.
Mr Zissman sees it differently. 'This is a very parochial city,' he said.
'People are interested in what's happening. Even if you think the
Conservative government is lacking in popularity, the Labour council is no
more popular.'
Once the question of management is stripped out, there are similarities
between the Conservative and Labour approaches to future policy. Both put
education as their top priority. The Conservatives have put forward a plan
to offer free development land to companies willing to undertake the
refurbishment or new construction of schools. Mrs Stewart said: 'My top
priority is to get more money into the schools, trying to do it within the
budget process.'
After that, Mrs Stewart puts priority on social services and housing, and Mr
Zissman on law and order. Now that big spending projects for the city
centre, with the building of the International Convention Centre and the
amelioration of the traffic system, have been either completed or are under
way, the parties' attention is directed to the suburbs - where the votes
are.
But the burning local issue is one which the political parties can do very
little about: the shutting of old hospitals and the plans for new medical
complexes. Conservative and Labour alike oppose the plans. Dr Chinn
remarked: 'Any party which came out in favour would be massacred.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
