<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Banham changes Ridings' boundary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shift in the boundary between the East and West Ridings of Yorkshire is
the only change in plans from Sir John Banham's Local Government Commission
for Lincolnshire, Humberside and North Yorkshire compared with its
provisional findings for the area last June.
Lincolnshire will remain the same while the other two counties each see the
removal of one 'tier' of government, and the amalgamation of several
existing authorities.
The change shifts Selby District Council, and the portion of Boothferry
District Council which includes Goole, from the East Riding to the West
Riding. The new creation is closer to the old boundaries of the West Riding,
according to Sir John, but produces a disparate collection of communities
spreading from the banks of the River Humber to the border with Lancashire.
York is to be turned into 'greater York' in a move welcomed by the local
Confederation of British Industry. Surrounding district councils attacked
the plan, and said it did not have popular support.
</TEXT>
