<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Employers' worries 'hamper NVQs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Concern over both the costs and the content of the new competence-based
National Vocational Qualifications and Scottish Vocational Qualifications
remain reasons for the failure of employers to introduce them into the
workplace, according to a survey published today.
NVQs and SVQs are intended by the government to be a main plank of its
strategy to improve vocational training. But academics have criticised NVQs
because the qualifications are based on what people can do, with little
examination of what is known or understood about a subject.
The survey, carried out by the Institute of Management Studies for the
Department of Employment, was the first big assessment of NVQs and SVQs. It
estimated that, for the UK as a whole, about 5 per cent of companies were
using NVQs and SVQs.
The survey found that large companies made greater use of the qualifications
than small companies. The institute added: 'While the majority of employers
in the survey had heard of NVQs/SVQs, only a relatively small number had
started using them.'
NVQs and SVQs: Early Indications of Employers' Take-up and Use. IMS report
259. BEBC, PO Box 1496, Parkstone, Poole, Dorset BH12 3YD. Pounds 45.
</TEXT>
