FT  25 JAN 94 / MPs sharply criticise second Welsh agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, WALES and WEST CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The conduct of another Welsh development agency was sharply criticised by
members of the Commons public accounts committee last night. The MPs also
questioned the effectiveness of the Welsh Office in scrutinising the
Development Board for Rural Wales and for the lack of disciplinary
sanctions.
The attack followed the committee's scathing report last year on some
activities of the Welsh Development Agency.
The committee yesterday questioned Mr Michael Flanagan, the agency's chief
executive, and Mr Michael Scholar, the Welsh Office permanent secretary,
after a report by the National Audit Office criticised the agency's housing
allocation policy and a car leasing scheme. This report followed a finding
by the ombudsman for local administration that there had been gross
maladministration.
The agency allocated houses under a published set of rules but also under
another, unpublished set. The housing officer was involved in allocating a
house to himself and to his former wife. Under a car leasing scheme, there
was irregular expenditure of Pounds 27,000 in 1991-92.
Mr Robert Sheldon MP, the committee chairman and Labour MP for
Ashton-under-Lyne, referred to it as a 'sad story', and Mr Michael Shersby,
Tory MP for Uxbridge, said it was 'a disgraceful state of affairs'.
Mr Scholar and Mr Flanagan acknowledged that it had been unlawful to
allocate houses under unpublished rules.
Several MPs commented on the lack of sanctions taken against the agency by
the Welsh Office. Mr Scholar said that Mr Flanagan had been rebuked and the
housing officer admonished but no other disciplinary action had been taken
yet.
Asked what action had been taken by the Welsh Office in the light of the
criticism of the Welsh Development Agency, Mr Scholar said a compliance
review of all the Welsh non-departmental public bodies had been set in
train, and also an efficiency scrutiny of the Welsh Office's sponsorship of
these agencies.
</TEXT>
