<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Aspin's deputy named as defence secretary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday named Mr William Perry, deputy US defence
secretary, to move up into the top Pentagon post in place of Mr Les Aspin,
taking on a position that Mr Clinton has found difficulty filling to his
satisfaction. He said Mr Perry was 'a real pro' who had 'the right vision
for the job'.
After asking Mr Aspin to resign, Mr Clinton had named retired Admiral Bobby
Ray Inman as his successor, but Adm Inman last week withdrew his name,
complaining of a conspiracy of newspaper columnists against him.
Although Mr Clinton said yesterday that the job was 'absolutely,
categorically not offered to anyone else', efforts were made to interest
Senator Sam Nunn, chairman of the Senate armed services committee, or former
Senator Warren Rudman, a respected Republican expert on defence and
budgetary issues.
Mr Perry, a 66-year-old mathematician whose role as number two at the
Pentagon has centred on management and acquisition issues, told the White
House on Saturday that if pressed for an immediate decision, he would have
to say no, for family reasons.
By Sunday afternoon, however, he had agreed to take the job.
In President Jimmy Carter's administration, Mr Perry headed the Pentagon's
research operations and was an early champion of stealth technology.
Before returning to Washington last year he was managing director of
Hambrecht &amp; Quist, a San Francisco investment banking firm, and headed a
Silicon Valley consultancy.
He said yesterday that implementing the force structure proposed by Mr
Aspin's 'Bottom Up Review' within Mr Clinton's proposed defence budget would
be difficult but achieveable.
'In order to carry out the Bottom Up Review with the funds proposed for it
we will have to manage the Pentagon very well,' he said.
Although he is expected to be more organised than the intellectually fertile
but sometimes unfocused Mr Aspin, Mr Perry's limited political or foreign
policy experience means he is unlikely to be the answer Mr Clinton has been
looking for to the shortcomings in his national security decision-making
structures.
Mr Aspin will stay at the Pentagon until Mr Perry has been through
confirmation by the Senate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
