<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / US moves on protesters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US Supreme Court ruled yesterday that anti-abortion protesters who block
clinics can be sued under the tough US racketeering law, Reuter reports from
Washington.
The decision by Chief Justice William Rehnquist overturned a lower court
ruling that anti-abortion protesters were not covered by the federal
racketeering law.
Judge Rehnquist said the racketeering law does not require proof that the
protesters' actions were motivated by an economic purpose. Anti-abortion
groups argued they were motivated by moral and political reasons and thus
were not covered by the law.
The ruling was a major victory for the Clinton administration and for
abortion rights activists, who have long sought to use the racketeering law
to deter the blocking of entrances to clinics and the harassment of
employees and women seeking abortions.
</TEXT>
