<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Clinton, riding high, heads for rough country: On eve of the
State of the Union address. Jurek Martin reviews the state of the president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
By one yardstick, President Bill Clinton has good reason to look forward to
presenting his first official State of the Union address to Congress
tonight.
He will speak after a first year of legislative achievement unmatched by any
newly-elected president since Dwight Eisenhower in 1953, with the economy
cruising along very nicely and a budget deficit now projected at a mere
Dollars 180bn (Pounds 122bn), and, in consequence, with his own popularity
rising back to where it was when he assumed office.
He could take encouragement from the fact that his initial address to
Congress last February (technically not a State of the Union message) was
considered by all a raging success and that he has clearly taken the
leadership in enunciating public concerns about the great issues of the
moment - healthcare, crime and gun control, and reform of the welfare
system.
By another measurement, however, his remains an afflicted presidency, still
struggling to find consistency. He is currently embarrassed by problems
finding a new defence secretary, troubled by the Whitewater investigations
into his financial dealings in Arkansas in the 1980s, and, overseas,
disturbed that the Russian commitments to reform given him in Moscow only 10
days ago now look very suspect, while the situation in Bosnia deteriorates
by the hour.
Moreover, both parties in Congress remain deeply divided over what to do
about healthcare, crime and welfare reform, reducing the president's chances
of clear cut victories. Mr Clinton declared over the weekend that 'gridlock'
was over, a post-North American Free Trade Agreement sentiment officially
shared by the leadership of both parties, but declarations of its demise may
yet, like reports of Mark Twain's death, prove premature.
Even before any of the big issues come to the crunch on Capitol Hill, his
most immediate problem is next month's Senate debate on the balanced budget
amendment. Passage against his wishes would not only encourage Republicans
but might persuade Democrats up for re-election in November to desert the
presidential cause on other matters.
Also, Ross Perot, the third force in contemporary US politics, promised over
the weekend to mobilise his troops in favour of the balanced budget and
against healthcare reform. Many members of Congress are afraid of his
grassroots power.
Still, one of the great advantages of the ceremonial State of the Union
message is that it gives the president an unchallenged pulpit to go over the
heads of a carping capital and talk to the nation about his agenda and
rationale. The specifics may be lightly touched on but the broad themes are
intended to strike important national chords.
Mr Clinton has done this effectively in a series of recent speeches on the
question of individual responsibilities to social issues aimed both at
minorities and at the broad middle class. Tonight's address is likely to
draw heavily on the one he gave last October in Memphis at the Rev Martin
Luther King's old church in which he urged communities not to wait for the
government to solve all their problems.
This theme cuts across party lines and underpins Mr Clinton's own claim to
be a 'new kind of Democrat' practising simultaneously fiscal responsibility
and a tough, but caring, approach to social problems, including crime (the
president may well endorse the populist drive to impose mandatory life
sentences on anyone convicted of three violent offences).
Inter-connected inside this framework are all the component parts of his
ambitious domestic agenda, which, he is convinced with some justification,
are broadly what the country wants and needs. Several recent polls have
found that crime and healthcare have supplanted the economy, the focus of
his first year, as the dominant national concern.
It is likely, therefore, that domestic issues will dwarf foreign policy in
tonight's address. Whatever his apparent difficulties overseas, the public,
into which he is so finely tuned, simply does not follow the twists and
turns in Russia, Bosnia and elsewhere.
A Washington Post poll published over the weekend found 67 per cent
satisfied with his conduct of external relations, even though a
hypercritical Washington establishment fumes daily over the shortcomings of
his foreign policy team's performance.
Thus it may be sufficient for Mr Clinton merely to point to the Nafta
victory and Uruguay Round trade accord, to promise to maintain pressure on
Japan to open its markets, to highlight Nato's new approach to the former
Warsaw Pact countries and to re-emphasise his commitment to democracy and
reform in Russia and elsewhere in eastern Europe.
He could, if he wanted, borrow one line from his speech in Brussels two
weeks ago about the impossibility of the US controlling 'every event in
every country every day'.
But the Clinton target tonight will be the audiences that helped put him in
office to solve national problems. He will claim he has made a very good
start but that much tough sledding lies ahead. Not long after he sits down,
predictable applause ringing in his ears, he will be finding out again how
tough it can be.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
