<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Hosokawa begins moves to salvage political reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the Japanese prime minister, yesterday made no headway
in trying to salvage an agreement on political reform before his time runs
out at the end of the week.
Parliamentary officials of the ruling seven-party coalition last night met
members of the opposition Liberal Democratic party to try to form a joint
panel of the upper and lower houses, as a forum for hammering out a
compromise.
They failed to agree, and plan to meet again today.
The LDP blamed 'co-ordination' problems. The party is divided between a
minority who seek a watered-down version of the political reform plans - the
leadership's official line - and a majority who have strong reservations
over the proposed abandonment of Japan's multi-seat constituency system.
In one small sign of possible progress, the leadership of the Social
Democratic (socialist) party, the largest coalition partner, said it was
ready to meet the LDP. There proved to be more anti-reform socialist rebels
than had been expected, and it was their defection which resulted in the
upper house voting down the reform plans last Friday.
If, as is likely, Mr Hosokawa fails to get an agreement by the end of this
parliamentary session on Saturday at midnight, the bills will expire. Mr
Hosokawa will then be under pressure to carry out his implied promise to
resign, despite the fact that he is Japan's most popular politician.
The Keidanren, the leading business federation, yesterday called on him not
to dissolve parliament and call a snap general election. Prolonged political
uncertainty would further damage the economy, warned Mr Gaishi Hiraiwa, the
Keidanren's chairman. He called on the government and opposition to join
forces to enact political reform and to complete a long-delayed economic
stimulus package forthwith. Political observers believe that if Mr Hosokawa
does resign, he would hand over the prime ministership to a leading member
of the seven-party coalition, rather than calling an election straight away.
Mr Tsutomu Hata, foreign minister and leader of the Japan Renewal party, set
up last June by defectors from the LDP, or Mr Masayoshi Takemura, leader of
the New Harbinger party, another former LDP splinter group, are mentioned by
Japanese political commentators as front-runners for the job.
</TEXT>
