</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The former chairman of Greece's largest commercial bank died in hospital
yesterday after being shot four times at close range, Reuter reports from
Athens. Mr Mihalis Vranopoulos, former National Bank of Greece chairman,
died shortly after the left-wing November 17 guerrilla group said it shot
him for his role in the purchase of the state-owned Heracles General Cement
Company in 1992.
The deal prompted cries of unfair competition from rival bidders and
accusations of bribes by opposition parties. Greece's socialists reopened
the investigation of the case after winning elections and promised a full
investigation.
