<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Consortium edges nearer to bid for Independent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The consortium put together by Mr Andreas Whittam Smith, the main founder of
The Independent newspaper, yesterday edged closer to making a bid for
Newspaper Publishing, the company that publishes The Independent and the
Independent on Sunday.
The consortium said it was considering making an offer for the 52.9 per cent
of the company held by institutional shareholders and not already controlled
by its members.
The move came after Mirror Group Newspapers - a member of the consortium -
confirmed it was ready to take 40 per cent of the loss-making company. The
consortium also includes the founders of The Independent and the two largest
existing shareholders, the Spanish and Italian newspaper groups El Pas and
La Republica.
Detailed discussions on the price of any such deal are likely to start
immediately as pressure is mounting for an early resolution of the
struggling group's future.
Noting the announcement, Mr Ian Hay Davison, chairman of Newspaper
Publishing, said a committee of non-executive directors would consider the
proposal. It would also discuss with the consortium the proposed terms.
It is believed that potential rival bidders, such as Mr Tony O'Reilly's
Independent Newspapers of Ireland, are waiting to see what the Whittam
Smith-MGN consortium proposes before making a counter-offer.
However, it now appears that Mr O'Reilly might have to make a full bid for
the company if he wants to block a consortium bid. The members of the
consortium have signed undertakings that no one else can come in unless all
agree.
Mr Hay Davison said the board committee would 'assess the alternatives
available to Newspaper Publishing on their merits'.
Further delay is likely, however. It is unlikely that any alternative bids
for the company will be put before this Thursday's routine monthly board
meeting.
Mr Whittam Smith expressed delight at the consortium agreement. He said it
meant 'our editorial independence will be assured and we will be able to
reduce our costs with increased investment in The Independent and the
Independent on Sunday.' MGN has said it will renounce the right to vote on
the hiring and firing of editors.
Mr David Montgomery, chief executive of MGN, conceded that Newspaper
Publishing would not be a goldmine, but said it represented a good long-term
investment that would take the popular newspaper group into a different
sector of the market.
At The Independent, journalists rejected the proposed deal with MGN as
incompatible with the editorial independence of the titles. The National
Union of Journalists chapel (branch) resolution also questioned whether Mr
Montgomery was a suitable person to be involved with The Independent.
Once a formal bid is made, the issue will have to be considered under
monopolies legislation. A reference to the Monopolies Commission is
automatic for newspaper deals involving combined circulations of 300,000
unless the life of a paper is threatened.
Lex, Page 22
Future in the Mirror, Page 11
</TEXT>
