<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / UK renews export cover to Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government yesterday renewed export insurance cover to Lebanon
for the first time since 1977.
The announcement coincided with an hour-long meeting in London yesterday
between Mr John Major, UK prime minister, and Mr Rafik Hariri, his Lebanese
counterpart. It signals increasing international confidence in returning
political and commercial stability following the end of the 1975-90 civil
war.
British ministers hope the move will make it easier for UK companies to bid
for some of the Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.7bn) of work to rebuild Beirut. The
initial credit facility is understood to be for Pounds 50m.
Premiums will depend on what assessment officials make of the risk of
operating in Lebanon.
Mr Richard Needham, British trade minister, said yesterday: 'The British
Export Credits Guarantee Department is one of the first export credit
agencies to go back on cover following the cessation of hostilities.'
British officials believe that French authorities have also provided an
export credit facility and that Italy has signed a trade protocol with
Lebanon.
Glimmer of confidence, Page 20
