<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / HK democracy blow for Patten
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Governor Chris Patten's chances of getting the so-called non-controversial
parts of his democracy legislation through Hong Kong's legislature narrowed
at the weekend when the Legislative Council's biggest political party said
it would seek to amend his plans.
The Liberal party, a 15-member coalition of conservative politicians in the
60-strong council, said that in the interests of getting Britain and China
back to the negotiating table it would propose deleting all reference to
next year's Legco polls from a bill working its way through the council. But
it would support the governor's proposals for forthcoming local government
elections.
If the Liberals' amendment succeeds Mr Patten would be placed in a virtually
untenable position. One of the reasons talks between Britain and China broke
down late last year was the UK refusal to consider the colony's local
government elections separately from those for Legco.
Observer, Page 13
