<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / OECD joblessness study focuses on capital tax: Long-term
unemployment linked to crime and drugs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Higher taxation on capital to offset reductions in non-wage labour costs is
one of several radical proposals for reducing unemployment suggested in a
study by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.
The draft policy conclusion of the long-awaited report, which is likely to
shape debate at President Bill Clinton's Group of Seven jobs summit in
March, emphasises the need for greater flexibility in labour markets to
increase employment, but falls short of advocating wide US-style wage
differentials and labour market deregulation.
The report, a copy of which has been obtained by the Financial Times, has
just been sent to the 24 member governments. It is not due to be published
until June. It finds little evidence that trade with low-wage countries is a
big cause of unemployment in the developed world. It does, however,
explicitly link long-term unemployment to rising levels of crime and drug
abuse and an 'unravelling of the social fabric'.
Mr Jean-Claude Paye, the OECD secretary-general who was commissioned by
member states to produce the report in June 1992, rejected the accusation
that he was being alarmist about the effects of unemployment. 'There is a
link between unemployment and crime and drugs, and I would be happy to see a
mandate from member countries to study that link,' he said in an interview.
He said the US had much more employment flexibility than Europe but at the
expense of social solidarity, and he warned that a policy emphasis on
flexibility and deregulation alone could lead to social dislocation.
The OECD's policy proposals have eight points at their core: nurture an
entrepreneurial climate; improve labour force skills and competences;
enhance the diffusion of technological knowhow; increase wage and labour
cost flexibility; reform job security provisions; increase working-time
flexibility; encourage a switch from passive to active labour market
measures; and reform benefit systems to increase work incentives.
On cutting non-wage labour costs, the report says: 'A significant
revenue-neutral cut in payroll taxes could yield important increases in
employment over the medium term.' With international co-ordination, the
burden should be switched to consumption taxes, environmental taxes or
higher effective taxation of capital income.
On training, the report says that levy systems - where companies pay a
proportion of the wage bill on training or pay an equivalent levy - have
been a disappointment. But the OECD does suggest that countries should
reform accounting standards for training expenditure and allow the costs of
training to be written off over the lifetime of the asset and not just when
the cost was incurred.
It also argues that statutory minimum wages can have a negative effect on
employment and that their redistributive goals can be achieved more
effectively through income supplements.
Economics Notebook, Page 19
</TEXT>
