FT  24 JAN 94 / Observer: Poisoned chalice
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who will get the job of selling Europe to the Brits? The search for a
candidate to run the European Commission's London office is looking
increasingly jinxed; at least one prospective applicant has declined the
offer. The recruitment has stalled thanks to an internal EC argument over
whether to pick an in-house candidate or gamble on an outsider.
Sir Leon Brittan, the EU's chief trade negotiator and senior UK
commissioner, believes that spreading the net will ensure the best quality.
Other bureaucrats, notably David Williamson, secretary general, are pushing
for an insider to run the 25-strong London office. So Geoff Martin, the
temporary stand-in, must rate his chances. However, the post has been
unfilled since last May which raises the question of whether it is being
kept open for an unlucky Tory MEP who loses a seat in the forthcoming
European elections. Surely not.
