<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Performance pay and bargaining rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MIKE CLANCY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your article, 'Power workers accept merit pay' (January 15/16),
requires clarification. The new agreement for professional and supervisory
staff in Eastern Electricity covers a package of terms and conditions,
including the introduction of performance-related pay (PRP). However, the
statement that the trade union's acceptance of PRP ends our participation in
pay bargaining for this group does not reflect the terms of the agreement.
Performance appraisal categories will determine precise individual
increases, but the product of the trade union's negotiations will be paid as
a minimum to individuals who meet or exceed targets. In addition, we have
secured the right to represent members over objective setting and their
year-end appraisal rating. Indeed, the new scheme does not go into full
effect until 1996; this provides a phasing-in period negotiated by the trade
unions due to our reservations about the efficiency of PRP as a method of
rewarding and motivating professional staff.
It is important that the impression given by the article is corrected, as
too often trade unions are portrayed as unable to come to terms with PRP. We
have successfully combined the protection of collective pay negotiations
with rewards for individual achievement in the PRP system. There is nothing
in this acceptance of PRP that is incompatible with strong trade union
representation into the future.
Mike Clancy,
area secretary,
Engineers' and Managers'
Association,
Flaxman House,
Gogmore Lane,
Chertsey,
Surrey KT16 9JS
</TEXT>
