<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Cleveland carve-up sets off election row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A fresh controversy has grown from last week's decision to replace Cleveland
County Council with four unitary authorities. The argument is over whether
elections for the four should be held in May this year or next.
The new councils will come into being in April next year and will have the
same boundaries as the present four districts. The argument about the
election date has split local parties. Cross-party district councillors tend
to favour delaying elections until the new unitary authorities are in place
next year.
But some county councillors believe that district representatives who expect
to start handling county work soon should seek a mandate from the electorate
as soon as possible.
District councillors will play an important role between now and April next
year in determining how their authorities absorb the roles of the doomed
county council, including education and social services. The council has
21,865 employees and a Pounds 404m annual budget.
County council Tory group leader and Middlesbrough district councillor Mrs
Hazel Pearson, who is 'sad and disillusioned' by the government's handling
of the reorganisation, said: 'It would be totally wrong that a council
elected at district level takes on the mantle of a county role without going
to the electorate.'
Cleveland's Labour leader Mr Paul Harford agrees. 'People who are going to
dictate the level of services should put their manifesto to the electorate
before, not after,' he said.
Mr Bryan Hanson, Labour leader of Hartlepool district council, said: 'We're
always getting new duties to perform, like Care in the Community last year.
I see this as us recovering those duties we lost in 1974 (the last
reorganisation). Whether we have elections before or immediately after is
irrelevant.'
The timing of elections in Cleveland has wide implications as it is the
first mainland county on which a reorganisation decision has been made.
</TEXT>
