<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Banham attacked over council plans: Controversy dogs reform
proposals in north-east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Local Government Commission is expected today to recommend the abolition
of Humberside and North Yorkshire county councils and the retention of
Lincolnshire.
Sir John Banham, commission chairman, faces widespread opposition to his
proposal to create three new local-authority areas, to be called 'Ridings'
even though they will not correspond to the long-standing North, East and
West Ridings of Yorkshire that were abolished when Humberside was created in
1974.
In Lincolnshire, he is expected to confirm his provisional recommendation
that the two-tier status quo, with a county council and eight smaller
district councils, should be maintained, in spite of guidance from Mr John
Gummer, the environment secretary, that he expects all-purpose unitary
authorities to be created.
The Association of District Councils will call for Mr Gummer to reject the
option, suggesting that smaller unitary authorities could be created.
Hull and York would become unitary authorities under the plans for north of
the Humber.
Local Conservative MPs have attacked the 'Riding' label, as the old Ridings
included large tracts of the county, including Leeds, Kirklees and
Sheffield, which are now run under metropolitan authorities.
The original proposal for the North Riding - which was to include Richmond,
Northallerton and Scarborough - was denounced as 'Shambleshire' by the
Association of District Councils on the grounds that it would be
unmanageably big. The East Riding was to include Beverley, Goole and Selby,
while the West Riding would be based on Harrogate and Skipton.
Sir John also faces calls from Cleveland for his resignation
after it was revealed in a local newspaper that he had told the
Plymouth-based Western Morning News that he favoured the idea of one large
unitary council for Cornwall.
Sir John, a Cornishman, said that if a county-wide Cornwall council were
abolished, 'the representation of Cornwall would go by default and it would
more difficult for Cornwall to punch its weight in the south-west'.
Mr Ronald Allan, editor of the Middlesbrough-based Evening Gazette, which
has campaigned against Sir John's proposal that Cleveland should be split
into four unitary authorities, pointed out that Teesside's population was
almost identical to Cornwall's. He said: 'The fact that Sir John has used
the arguments that he rejected for Teesside to push the case to retain
Cornwall as a county shows that there is absolutely no logic to this whole
commission.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
