<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Builders fear lost business from stamp duty changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes to stamp duty rules announced in the Budget are causing alarm among
housebuilders and commercial property companies, which fear that deals
currently being concluded may be disrupted.
Accountancy firm Price Waterhouse says the changes will mean that, for the
first time, stamp duty will be applied fully to part-exchange house sales,
land swaps between builders and internal leases agreed between parent
companies and subsidiaries.
Until now stamp duty on exchanges of property or land has been levied only
on cash paid to make up the difference in the value between the properties.
With the threshold for stamp duty set at Pounds 60,000, this has meant that
little or no duty was paid.
Price Waterhouse claims that the Pounds 70m the Treasury has estimated it
will raise in 1994-95 is small compared with the disruption and extra costs
to industry from additional property valuations.
The Law Society has written to the Inland Revenue seeking clarification of
the changes, which have already come into effect. It wants any subsequent
modification of the rules by parliament to be backdated to allow companies
and individuals to reclaim stamp duty paid unfairly.
About Pounds 55m of house sales involve part-exchange deals. The
Housebuilders Federation fears that some purchasers who had not expected to
pay stamp duty will pull out or seek to renegotiate terms.
The changes will also affect land swaps, in which builders with too much
land in one region exchange with a builder with excess land elsewhere.
Mr Roger Humber, director of the Housebuilders Federation said: 'These
transactions do not create any immediate profit for the companies but
improve the efficiency of the industry. Any subsequent gain can be taxed in
the normal way when properties are sold.
'Stamp duty on part-exchange house sales will raise only Pounds 3m but will
add an unnecessary complication to transactions.'
The British Property Federation is concerned that companies which negotiate
leases with subsidiaries for 'good internal accounting reasons' will be
penalised by having to pay stamp duty on these deals.
It says companies renegotiating terms of lease arrangements will have to pay
stamp duty on the full market value of the building even though there has
been no change in ownership or occupation.
Mr Don Draper of Price Waterhouse said: 'The government may find it has no
alternative but to withdraw the proposals.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
