<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Brian Redhead - Voice of Today: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It has often been said (mainly by its producers, admittedly) that the Today
programme on BBC Radio 4 sets the day's agenda for politicians and
journalists alike. Any truth in this should be credited chiefly to Brian
Redhead, who died yesterday at the age of 64.
A scholarship boy from Newcastle upon Tyne, he joined the Manchester
Guardian when he came down from Cambridge, and rose rapidly to become editor
of its sister paper, the Manchester Evening News. When he left in 1975 to
succeed Robert Robinson as presenter of Today, the breakfast programme was
mixing news and entertainment.
It was Redhead as much as a new generation of producers who turned it into
the grittier all-news programme which was sought out by Cabinet ministers
wishing to catch the ear of the prime minister early in the day. Baroness
Thatcher, who was a dedicated listener, said yesterday: 'The breadth and
depth of his knowledge were quite outstanding, and I always enjoyed being
interviewed by him.'
Mr John Major said: 'I shall remember him for his feisty interviewing style
and the ever-present twinkle in his eye. He will be greatly missed.'
Redhead said the job was 'the best in journalism'. Just before 5am in the
Today office you could always hear him coming: he whistled all the way down
the long corridor from the lifts. It irritated some of his colleagues -
which only encouraged him, as did their grumbles about his intellectual
arrogance. They could not deny that he was well-read, quick, politically
astute, and could handle any interview at the drop of a hat.
His main interest outside journalism was religion. Yet it was only after
William, one of his four children, was killed in a car crash when he was 18
that Redhead became a regular churchgoer. He was due to retire this year
from Today and there had been talk of his then taking holy orders although
he recently denied this.
He leaves a widow, Jenni, two sons and a daughter.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
