<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Offence of 'racial violence' proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The creation of a new criminal offence of racial violence is proposed today
by the Commission on Social Justice.
Racial discrimination, says the commission, is a barrier to social justice
in Britain and a specific offence of racial violence is one of the measures
required to combat it.
The commission, which was set up by Mr John Smith, the Labour party leader,
also calls for the law against incitement to religious hatred in Northern
Ireland to be extended to the whole of the UK. It urges action to prohibit
employers from rejecting job applicants because of their religious
backgrounds.
The Commons home affairs committee is conducting an investigation into
racial attacks and is considering the value of a specific criminal offence
of racial harassment. Even if it recommends creating one, however, the
government is unlikely to do so.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, told the committee last week he was
not persuaded that the case for an offence of racial harassment had been
established. He said the courts could already take all relevant factors into
account when passing sentence under existing law, and the main problem was
the difficulty which the police often faced in identifying those responsible
for racial attacks.
Mr Howard said that if it could be shown that any changes in the law were
needed, he would prefer to amend the existing Public Order Act rather than
introduce a new offence.
</TEXT>
