FT  24 JAN 94 / Clarke says Iraq case claim is 'tosh'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke yesterday dismissed as 'tosh' and 'outrageous' claims that
he had conspired with other ministers to suppress evidence in the failed
Matrix Churchill case.
The chancellor said that if the Scott inquiry stated he had suppressed
evidence in the Matrix Churchill case, 'I would carry on protesting my
innocence but I would resign'.
Speaking two days before Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, is due to
give evidence to the inquiry, Mr Clarke said: 'The suggestion of conspiring
with ministers to suppress evidence to see that innocent men are convicted
is outrageous.
'It is, I suggest, tosh and far removed from anything you could picture.' He
told BBC TV's Breakfast with Frost programme that the allegations had caused
him 'more annoyance than anything else in my political career'.
Mr Clarke was one of the ministers who signed certificates seeking to
prevent secret government documents being made available to the defence in
the Matrix Churchill trial.
