<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Britons show up poorly in charity survey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's notion of itself as a philanthropic nation that gives generously
to charity is challenged by an international study published today.
It shows that, while a majority of Britons make donations to charity, the
amounts they give do not bear comparison with donations made overseas. A
British charity supporter donates an average of only Pounds 2 per month -
one-sixth of the amount of a US counterpart, and far lower than Canadian,
French or Spanish donors.
The survey, the first international comparative study of giving and
volunteering, illustrates the seriousness of the dilemma facing the British
voluntary sector. It is coming under increasing pressure to provide
additional services while the public still finances charities with small
change.
The British are far more likely to contribute relatively small amounts than
donors in any of the other four countries surveyed: 19 per cent of British
donors give less than Pounds 1 per month, compared with only 2 per cent in
Canada and France, 4 per cent in the US and 8 per cent in Spain. While 11
per cent of British donors are shown by the survey to give more than Pounds
10 per month, they are overshadowed by 28 per cent in Canada, 26 per cent in
the US and 21 per cent in Spain.
The bright spot in the findings for British charities is that the proportion
of the population donating to charity - 65 per cent - was the highest of any
of the countries surveyed except Spain, where the results were influenced by
large numbers of people buying tickets for charity lotteries. But although
only 27 per cent of the French population had made a recent charitable
donation when the survey was conducted, the average amount given was Pounds
10.10.
One explanation for the disparity may be that street and door-to-door
collections remain the most common way of raising money from individuals in
Britain. French donors are more likely to respond to advertisements or
appeal letters.
Mr Michael Brophy, executive director of the Charities Aid Foundation which
co-ordinated the research, said that while giving to good causes was a
strong and established part of the British culture, the results suggested
that 'we do not value the role played by charities to the extent that some
other countries do'.
International Giving and Volunteering, 1st edition. Charities Aid
Foundation, 48 Pembury Road, Tonbridge, Kent TN9 2JD. Pounds 16.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P673  Trusts.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
