<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Midlands business warns on recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business leaders in the Midlands have warned Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, that the tax increases taking effect in April could choke
economic recovery unless they are balanced by a cut in interest rates.
Mr Bryan Townsend, chairman of the West Midlands regional council of the
Confederation of British Industry, said: 'The anticipated cut in interest
rates is necessary to make sure that the tax increases don't dampen down
consumer confidence.'
Mr Geoff Nicholls, chairman of the East Midlands CBI, said that if the new
taxation had the effect of cutting the public's confidence then it would
halt recovery.
Although the business chiefs agree that there is steady growth in the
economy, in the east Midlands there is concern about the rise of sterling to
around DM2.60. This provides, in Mr Nicholl's view, further justification
for a cut in interest rates. 'Our worry is primarily that, if we keep them
high, the pound will stay high.'
</TEXT>
