FT  24 JAN 94 / Ulster hopes recede further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hopes of a peace deal in Northern Ireland faded further yesterday when Mr
Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein president, urged the UK government to tell unionists
that their future lay with 'the rest of the Irish people', Tim Coone and
David Owen write.
Interviewed on RTE Radio in Dublin, Mr Adams said that if the government did
so, Sinn Fein would be 'flexible' and would seek 'a peaceful development
towards an accord which everyone can give allegiance to'.
His remarks dealt a further blow to faltering hopes of peace because such a
move would require an unlikely climbdown from the government. Ministers have
consistently said they will not join the ranks of the 'persuaders'.
Yesterday's comments came as the Loyalist paramilitary group, the Ulster
Freedom Fighters, said it carried out Saturday's two fire bomb attacks on
stores in Dundalk in the Republic of Ireland.
Editorial comment, Page 13
