<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / London hospitals to learn fate next month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Decisions on the future of some of London's best-known hospitals have been
deferred until next month.
An announcement had been scheduled for this week, but work on a final
package to be presented by Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, is
continuing.
The government is committed to cutting hospital beds in the capital and
shifting resources to family doctor and community services. But complex and
politically sensitive considerations are involved. If a package is agreed
this week the announcement is now likely to come around February 2 but it
could be delayed further.
One of the most controversial decisions involves Guy's and St Thomas'
teaching hospitals. Guy's &amp; St Thomas' Trust Board was asked to consider
ways of locating all services at one hospital, but it responded with a
proposal to retain both sites.
Since the trust board made its recommendation in November, it has been asked
by the government to evaluate further possibilities including single-site
options. Among these have been the possibility of housing the hospital at St
Thomas', and moving King's College medical school to Guy's buildings.
Studies have shown that a combined Guy's and St Thomas' hospital could be
accommodated on either site but the trust board does not believe sufficient
capital funding would be available to achieve this. A twin-site solution is
therefore a strong possibility although several options remain before
ministers.
Another sensitive decision concerns the future of the Royal Marsden cancer
hospital's Chelsea buildings. A government-commissioned review of specialist
services has recommended a transfer to a site at Sutton, Surrey. This
provoked a powerful campaign to keep the Royal Marsden in Chelsea and a
decision to close it would court unpopularity for the Conservatives ahead of
May's local elections in London.
Some health service managers believe single-speciality hospitals such as the
Royal Marsden will not prove cost-effective in the new contract-based
internal market. An option for ministers would be to defer a decision,
leaving the market to decide whether the Royal Marsden has a future at
Chelsea.
The forthcoming decisions do not only concern hospitals facing possible
closure. Others risk the removal of services which could make them
uneconomic in the internal market.
The trust board of St Mary's, Paddington, has told the government that
proposals to withdraw its cardiac services would lose it Pounds 6m, or 6 per
cent of turnover, and another Pounds 2m in private patient fees - 28 per
cent of private-wing income. The hospital says that health service cardiac
surgery has risen from 440 to 660 cases this financial year and is forecast
to rise to 750 next year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
