<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 94 / Tories' tax record challenged: Treasury discloses tax burden
will be heavier than under Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party's credentials as the party of low taxation were under
fierce attack at Westminster last night after the publication of damaging
figures showing that the government will from April take more in tax from
the average family than Labour did.
The opposition parties pounced gleefully on the disclosure, with Labour
accusing the government of making the 'biggest tax demand in history'.
Labour hopes to make it impossible for the government to label it as the
high-tax party, a tactic the Conservatives used to great effect in the last
election.
Ominously for the government, some Tory backbench MPs were comparing the
political impact of the tax rises with the poll tax, which attracted
terminal unpopularity after it was implemented.
Tory MPs are now braced for pressure from their constituents over the
heavier tax burden once people realise how much extra tax they are paying.
People will find out either by being informed by the Inland Revenue or
simply by higher deductions taken from their pay in April.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke hit back at Labour, arguing that taxes would
always be lower under a Conservative government than under Labour in any
given year.
At the centre of the row, which arose just ahead of tomorrow's crucial House
of Commons debate on the finance bill, was the Treasury's disclosure that a
married man on average earnings with two children would this year pay 32.9
per cent of his earnings in direct and indirect taxes, rising to 35 per cent
in 1994-95. That compared with 32.2 per cent under Labour in 1978-1979.
Labour backed up its attack by highlighting official figures showing that
the proportion of gross domestic product taken by tax, excluding oil taxes,
would rise to 35 1/2 per cent in 1994-95 and 38 1/2 per cent in 1998-99.
That would outstrip the high of 36 3/4 per cent taken under the last Labour
government in 1975-76.
Interviewed on BBC TV's Breakfast with Frost, Mr Clarke insisted that
comparing current levels of taxation with the last year of a Labour
government was 'false'. He said: 'If you had a Labour chancellor now, taxes
would be much, much higher.
'At the very end of the Labour government, they did actually get tax down
below where we are at the moment, but that was one of the most irresponsible
things that Denis Healey (then chancellor) did in the run-up to the
election.'
But Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, accused his opposite number of 'tax
deception'.
'The facts are incontrovertible,' Mr Brown said. 'Tax is higher than under
Labour. Because the Tories will never tell the truth about their tax bills,
the country will never trust them on tax again.' Mr Alan Beith, the Liberal
Democrat Treasury spokesman, joined the attack, saying that forthcoming tax
increases were 'so large they have put the recovery at risk'.
Mr John Townend, chairman of the influential Tory backbench finance
committee, said it was vital for the government to re-establish itself as a
tax-cutting administration.
Low-tax flagship not so watertight
Smith keeps focus on big prize, Page 6
Observer, Page 13
</TEXT>
