<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / Finance and the Family: Scottish Provident
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Scottish Provident has cut payouts on short-term with-profits endowment
policies, but lifted longer-term payouts slightly. A 25-year policy, taken
out by a man aged 29 paying Pounds 30 a month, will pay Pounds 56,760 this
year, up 0.6 per cent from last year, while a 10-year policy would pay
Pounds 6,478, down 5.3 per cent.
The company has also changed its annual bonus system, with different bonus
levels on the sum assured and previous bonuses, rather than a single level
as before.
So rather than 5.2 per cent overall on life contracts paid last year, this
year the figures are 4 per cent on the sum assured and 6 per cent on
existing bonuses. This rewards longer term policy-holders more, as they have
accumulated more bonuses.
Terminal bonus scales have been adjusted to pay more to longer-term
policies. Bonus rates on unitised with-profits policies have also been cut,
from 8.5 per cent to 7.75 per cent for life, and 10 per cent to 9 per cent
for pensions.
Royal Life has increased payouts on with-profits endowments by increasing
terminal bonuses. The pay out on a 25-year policy is Pounds 61,172, up 10.1
per cent, and for a 10-year policy, Pounds 5,878, up 0.1 per cent.
Reversionary bonuses on unitised with profits policies have been held at 6.5
per cent, but terminal bonuses have been raised from 25 per cent to 30 per
cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Scottish Provident.
</CO>
<XX>
